    Items.insert({name:"PINWALE",category:"program",family:"database",status:"unknown",description:"[[Pinwale]] is the code name for an [[NSA]] database of archived foreign and domestic e-mails it has collected under its [[SIGINT]] efforts.  It is searchable by monitored NSA analysts. Its existence was first revealed by an NSA analyst who was trained to use it during 2005.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/17/us/17nsa.html|title=E-Mail Surveillance Renews Concerns in Congress|publisher=New York Times|date=June 16, 2009|authors=James Risen and Eric Lichtblau|accessdate=August 9, 2003}}</ref> However, according to \'\'Homeland Security Today\'\', Pinwale has in it much more than email, it also contains other forms of Internet data, and other forms of digital communications as well. Its software has built-in protections against collecting from any of the [[Five Eyes]] members. Unlike its successor  [[XKeyscore]], targets for PINWALE have to be approved beforehand by the [[United States Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court|FISC]].",relatedItems:[""]});
    Items.insert({name:"PRISM",category:"program",family:"process",status:"unknown",description:"[[PRISM]] ([[US-984XN]]) is a [[clandestine operation|clandestine]] [[mass surveillance|mass]] [[computer surveillance|electronic surveillance]] [[data mining]] program known to have been operated by the United States [[National Security Agency]] (NSA) since 2007.<ref name=\"WaPo1\">{{cite web| author = [[Barton Gellman|Gellman, Barton]]; [[Laura Poitras|Poitras, Laura]] | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/us-intelligence-mining-data-from-nine-us-internet-companies-in-broad-secret-program/2013/06/06/3a0c0da8-cebf-11e2-8845-d970ccb04497_story.html | title = US Intelligence Mining Data from Nine U.S. Internet Companies in Broad Secret Program |work=[[The Washington Post]] | date = June 6, 2013 | accessdate = June 15, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"apbraun061513\">{{cite news|last=Braun|first=Stephen|last2=Flaherty|first2=Anne|last3=Gillum|first3=Jack|last4=Apuzzo|first4=Matt|title=Secret to PRISM Program: Even Bigger Data Seizures|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/secret-prism-success-even-bigger-data-seizure|work = Associated Press |date=June 15, 2013 | accessdate = June 18, 2013}}</ref><!--{{#tag:ref|Multiple technology writers have asserted that the term \"PRISM\" refers to the computer systems tool that is used to gather intelligence rather than to the surveillance program itself, consistent with statements from U.S. government sources.<ref name=Cnet-McCullagh>{{cite news|author = [[Declan McCullagh|McCullagh, Declan]] |title=No Evidence of NSA\'s \'Direct Access\' to Tech Companies{{spaced ndash}} Sources Challenge Reports Alleging National Security Agency Is \'Tapping Directly into the Central Servers\'{{spaced ndash}} Instead, They Say, the Spy Agency Is Obtaining Orders under Process Created by Congress|url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13578_3-57588337-38/no-evidence-of-nsas-direct-access-to-tech-companies/|accessdate= June 15, 2013| publisher = [[CNET]] |date=June 7, 2013}}</ref> [[Marc Ambinder]], the co-author of a forthcoming book on national security and secrecy, described PRISM as \"a kick-ass [[graphical user interface|GUI]] that allows an analyst to look at, collate, monitor, and cross-check different data types provided to the NSA from internet companies located inside the United States.\"<ref>Ambinder, Marc (June 7, 2013).  [http://theweek.com/article/index/245360/solving-the-mystery-of-prism \"Solving the Mystery of PRISM\"]. \'\'The Compass\'\' (blog of \'\'[[The Week]]\'\'). Retrieved June 18, 2013.</ref> |group = \"Notes\"}}--> \'\'PRISM\'\' is a government [[code name]] for a data-collection effort known officially by the [[SIGINT Activity Designator|SIGAD]] {{nowrap|\'\'\'US-984XN\'\'\'}}.<ref>{{cite web | author = Chappell, Bill | url = http://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2013/06/06/189321612/nsa-reportedly-mines-servers-of-u-s-internet-firms-for-data |title=NSA Reportedly Mines Servers of US Internet Firms for Data | publisher=\'\'The Two-Way\'\' (blog of [[NPR]]) | date=June 6, 2013 | accessdate = June 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author = Staff | url = http://www.zdnet.com/prism-heres-how-the-nsa-wiretapped-the-internet-7000016565/ |title=PRISM: Here\'s How the NSA Wiretapped the Internet | publisher=[[ZDNet]] |date=June 8, 2013 | accessdate = June 15, 2013}}</ref> The Prism program collects stored Internet communications based on demands made to Internet companies such as Google Inc. under Section 702 of the [[FISA Amendments Act of 2008]]. The NSA can use these Prism requests to target communications that were encrypted when they traveled across the Internet backbone, to focus on stored data that telecommunication filtering systems discarded earlier,<ref name=\"WSJ20130821\">{{cite news|title=New Details Show Broader NSA Surveillance Reach - Programs Cover 75% of Nation\'s Traffic, Can Snare Emails|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324108204579022874091732470.html?mod=WSJEurope_hpp_LEFTTopStories|accessdate=21 August 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=20 August 2013|author=Siobhan Gorman and Jennifer Valentiono-Devries}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Graphic: How the NSA Scours Internet Traffic in the U.S.|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324108204579022874091732470.html?mod=WSJEurope_hpp_LEFTTopStories#project%3DNSA0820%26articleTabs%3Dinteractive|accessdate=21 August 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=20 August 2013}}</ref> and to get data that is easier to handle, among other things.<ref>{{cite news|title=What You Need to Know on New Details of NSA Spying|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424127887324108204579025222244858490.html?mod=WSJEurope_hpp_LEFTTopStories|accessdate=21 August 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=20 August 2013|author=Jennifer Valentiono-Devries and Siobhan Gorman}}</ref>The original \'\'Washington Post\'\' and \'\'Guardian\'\' articles reporting on PRISM noted that one of the leaked briefing documents said PRISM involves collection of data \"directly from the servers\" of several major Internet services providers.:<ref name=\"GenCoop\">{{cite web| author = Farivar, Cyrus | url=http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2013/06/new-leak-feds-can-access-anything-in-your-google-facebook-and-more/ |title = New Leak Shows Feds Can Access User Accounts for Google, Facebook and More{{spaced ndash}} Secret Slides Reveal Massive Government Spying, Tech Companies Dispute Reports |publisher = Ars Technica |date=June 6, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref>    * \'\'\'[[Microsoft]]\'\'\'<ref name=\"TechCrunch\">{{cite web | author = Lardinois, Frederic | url = http://techcrunch.com/2013/06/06/google-facebook-apple-deny-participation-in-nsa-prism-program/ |title=Google, Facebook, Dropbox, Yahoo, Microsoft and Apple Deny Participation in NSA PRISM Surveillance Program |publisher = [[TechCrunch]] |date=June 6, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref>* \'\'\'[[Yahoo!]]\'\'\'<ref name=\"WaPoJune12\">{{cite web | author = Lee, Timothy B.| url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/wonkblog/wp/2013/06/12/heres-everything-we-know-about-prism-to-date/ |title=Here\'s Everything We Know About PRISM to Date | publisher = \'\'Wonkblog\'\' (blog of \'\'[[The Washington Post]]\'\') |date=June 12, 2013 |accessdate=June 13, 2013}}</ref>* \'\'\'[[Facebook]]\'\'\' <ref name=\"TechCrunch\" />* \'\'\'[[Google]]\'\'\'<ref name=\"TechCrunch\" /><ref name=\"WaPoJune12\" />* \'\'\'[[Apple Inc.|Apple]]\'\'\'<ref name=\"AllThingsD\">{{cite web| author = Gannes, Liz | url=http://allthingsd.com/20130606/google-and-apple-outright-deny-theyre-helping-the-nsa-mine-data/ |title=Google, Apple and Facebook Outright Deny They\'re Helping the NSA Mine Data |publisher = [[All Things Digital]] |date = June 6, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2013}}</ref>* \'\'\'[[Dropbox (service)|Dropbox]]\'\'\'",relatedItems:["","[[TRAFFICTHIEF]]","[[MARINA]]","[[MAINWAY]]","[[FALLOUT]]","[[PINWALE]]","[[CONVEYANCE]]","[[NUCLEON]]"]});
